title: User defined ts-functions
text: slightly complex example, uses post processing function: easy make functions external packages ts-boxable, wrapping ts_. explicit namespace (e.g., dygraphs::dygraph), ts_ recognized package use delivers meaningful message package installed. Note ts_ function deals conversion stuff, ‘vectorizes’ function can used multiple time series. Let’ another look ts_forecast: three differences ts_rowsum example: First, function requires forecast package. installed, load_suggested ask user . Second, function use anonymous function, function(x) forecast::forecast(x, ...)$mean, also extracts $mean component result. Third, function ‘vectorized’, using ts_apply. causes process repeated time series object.
code: ts_prcomp <- ts_(function(x) predict(prcomp(x, scale = TRUE))) ts_prcomp(ts_c(mdeaths, fdeaths)) ts_dygraphs <- ts_(dygraphs::dygraph, class = "xts") ts_forecast <- ts_(function(x, ...) forecast::forecast(x, ...)$mean, vectorize = TRUE) ts_seas <- ts_(function(x, ...) seasonal::final(seasonal::seas(x, ...)), vectorize = TRUE)  ts_dygraphs(ts_c(mdeaths, EuStockMarkets)) ts_forecast(ts_c(mdeaths, fdeaths)) ts_seas(ts_c(mdeaths, fdeaths)) ts_forecast #> function (x, ...) #> { #>     load_suggested("forecast") #>     ff <- function(x, ...) { #>         stopifnot(ts_boxable(x)) #>         z <- (function(x, ...) forecast::forecast(ts_na_omit(x), #>             ...)$mean)(ts_ts(x), ...) #>         copy_class(z, x) #>     } #>     ts_apply(x, ff, ...) #> }

code: library(tsbox) x.ts <- ts_c(fdeaths, mdeaths) x.xts <- ts_xts(x.ts) x.df <- ts_df(x.xts) x.dt <- ts_dt(x.df) x.tbl <- ts_tbl(x.dt) x.zoo <- ts_zoo(x.tbl) x.tsibble <- ts_tsibble(x.zoo) x.tibbletime <- ts_tibbletime(x.tsibble) x.timeSeries <- ts_timeSeries(x.tibbletime) all.equal(ts_ts(x.timeSeries), x.ts)  # TRUE

Using remaining columns starting right , first Date, POSIXct, numeric character column used time column. character strings parsed anytime::anytime(). timestamp, time, indicates beginning period. remaining columns id columns. unique combination id columns points time series. Alternatively, time column value column explicitly named time value. explicit names used, column order ignored. columns detected automatically, message returned. example, following data frame standard structure understood tsbox: time value columns different names time value, still works returns message: can also use multiple id columns. converted ts object, multiple columns combined single value: Data frames must long format, single value columns . tsbox tries detect wide structures warns occur: data frames wide format, ts_long() can used conversion.
code: dta <-   dplyr::tribble(     ~series_name, ~time,        ~value,     "ser1",       "2001-01-01",  1,     "ser1",       "2002-01-01",  2,     "ser2",       "2001-01-01",  10,     "ser2",       "2002-01-01",  20,   ) ts_ts(dta) # Time Series: # Start = 2001 # End = 2002 # Frequency = 1 #      ser1 ser2 # 2001    1   10 # 2002    2   20 library(dplyr) dta %>%   dplyr::rename(     mytime = time,     myvalue = value   ) %>%   ts_ts() # [time]: 'mytime' [value]: 'myvalue' # Time Series: # Start = 2001 # End = 2002 # Frequency = 1 #      ser1 ser2 # 2001    1   10 # 2002    2   20 dta_multi_id <-   dplyr::tribble(     ~series_name, ~series_attribute,  ~time,        ~value,     "ser1",       "A",                  "2001-01-01",  1.5,     "ser1",       "A",                  "2002-01-01",  2.5,     "ser2",       "A",                  "2001-01-01",  10.5,     "ser2",       "A",                  "2002-01-01",  20.5,     "ser1",       "B",                  "2001-01-01",  1,     "ser1",       "B",                  "2002-01-01",  2,     "ser2",       "B",                  "2001-01-01",  10,     "ser2",       "B",                  "2002-01-01",  20   ) ts_ts(dta_multi_id) # Time Series: # Start = 2001 # End = 2002 # Frequency = 1 #      ser1_A ser2_A ser1_B ser2_B # 2001    1.5   10.5      1     10 # 2002    2.5   20.5      2     20 dta_wide <- ts_wide(ts_tbl(ts_c(mdeaths, fdeaths))) # # A tibble: 72 × 3 #    time       mdeaths fdeaths #    <date>       <dbl>   <dbl> #  1 1974-01-01    2134     901 #  2 1974-02-01    1863     689 #  3 1974-03-01    1877     827 #  4 1974-04-01    1877     677 #  5 1974-05-01    1492     522 #  6 1974-06-01    1249     406 #  7 1974-07-01    1280     441 #  8 1974-08-01    1131     393 #  9 1974-09-01    1209     387 # 10 1974-10-01    1492     582 # # … with 62 more rows ts_ts(dta_wide) # Using numeric [id] columns: 'mdeaths'. # Are you using a wide data frame? To convert, use 'ts_long()'. # Convert columns to character or factor to silence this message. ts_long(dta_wide)
